            <h2 id="about-storyloom">About StoryLoom</h2>
            
            <h3 id="what-is">What is StoryLoom?</h3>
            <p>StoryLoom functions as a dedicated, not-for-profit online library and digital archive. We curate and preserve free electronic texts and books with a singular, comprehensive focus on global folklore, mythology, and legends. Our collection aims to be a foundational resource for these rich oral traditions in written form, and all texts on the platform are completely free to read and download without any restriction whatsoever.</p>

            <h3 id="where-from">Where did StoryLoom come from?</h3>
            <p>The StoryLoom platform was conceived and developed as a major undergraduate university project. The primary goal of the endeavor was to create a centralized, durable digital repository specifically for global folktales. In building this archive, we drew very heavy inspiration—both architecturally and philosophically—from esteemed, long-standing digital preservation initiatives, most notably Project Gutenberg. We aim to honor their profound legacy of open access to literary works.</p>

            <h3 id="who-runs">Who runs StoryLoom?</h3>
            <p>At present, StoryLoom is maintained by the student-creator as an independent, ongoing undergraduate project. Information concerning the platform's founder, technical infrastructure details, and current project status is available for review on our dedicated <a href="/contact">Contact Us</a> page.</p>

            <h3 id="how-help">How can I help StoryLoom?</h3>
            <p>There are several vital ways for community members to support the StoryLoom project. The absolute best way to help is by volunteering your time to proofread recently added texts, ensuring their accuracy against original source materials. Additionally, we greatly appreciate assistance in reporting formatting bugs or errors, and helping us in our ongoing efforts to systematically categorize stories using recognized mythological motifs, such as the Aarne-Thompson-Uther system.</p>

            <h2 id="about-pubs">About StoryLoom publications</h2>

            <h3 id="only-books">Does StoryLoom publish only books?</h3>
            <p>Yes, that is essentially correct. StoryLoom is primarily focused on textual works. While we are keenly aware that folklore has its profound roots in oral storytelling traditions, the technical infrastructure we have built is specifically optimized for the long-term preservation and systematic categorization of written text files, with a strict adherence to the simple, resilient .txt format. This format ensures that these stories, once transcribed, remain accessible for centuries to come.</p>

            <h3 id="what-books">What texts does StoryLoom publish?</h3>
            <p>Our collection scope is strictly defined by the genres of mythology, fairy tales, and legends. We accept any book or text that fits these categories, provided it has definitively cleared United States copyright laws and is in the public domain. We place a very significant and explicit focus on curating works originally published in the 19th and early 20th centuries, as these are often rich with traditional folklore and are the foundational versions of well-known stories.</p>

            <h2 id="how-choose">How does StoryLoom choose texts to publish?</h2>
            <p>Unlike a commercial publishing house, StoryLoom does not operate with a rigid, gatekeeping editorial board. Our selection criteria are straightforward: if a text is verifiable folklore or mythology and can be legally shared because it is in the public domain, it is eligible to be woven into the archive's collection. The process is based on community-driven ingestion and volunteer efforts.</p>

            <h2 id="no-modern">Why don't you have any texts by Stephen King, Tolkien, etc.?</h2>
            <p>StoryLoom strictly adheres to a policy of only publishing books that are in the public domain within the United States. This legal requirement means that current blockbusters, recently published materials, and modern fantasy novels—such as those by Stephen King, J.R.R. Tolkien, and many other contemporary authors—are completely unavailable for our archive, as they remain heavily protected by existing copyright laws.</p>

            <h2 id="plain-text">Why is StoryLoom so set on using plain text?</h2>
            <p>The decision to focus exclusively on plain text is a foundational architectural choice, rooted deeply in the philosophy of long-term durability and universal accessibility. Plain text is, fundamentally, the only digital file format guaranteed to survive the unpredictable test of technological time. Formats like PDF, Word, or specialized e-reader files require complex software to be rendered, and they eventually become obsolete or require expensive, proprietary tools. Plain text (.txt), however, can be natively read by virtually any computer, phone, or operating system in the world, without the need for complex software or licenses. This ensures that these myths and legends are preserved indefinitely, protected from the entropy of digital formats, and remain easily accessible to anyone, anywhere, regardless of their technology.</p>

